column1: Data Supplied By: National Livestock Reporting Service
Data source: National Livestock Reporting Service
Please see terms of use here: https://www.mla.com.au/general/Terms-and-conditions/data-and-information/

Numbers were up this week with a high volume of weaners on offer however grown and yearling stock were sparse. Cows were also plentiful and were drafted in large lines often yarded in double pens while Slaughter bulls were in short supply. The buyer gallery had the usual regulars and Live export were active on younger steers, heifers and bulls.
Light weight or plain weaner steers started from 220c to 278c while better steers ranged from 280c to 344c lifting 8/10c/kg.  Weaner heifers also gained 8/10c with light weights selling from 150c to 200c and with better weight and frame sold from 220c to 272c/kg.  The limited yarding of yearlings recorded equal values with steers selling from 160c to 296c depending on quality and yearling heifers returned 200c to 278c/kg.
Grown steers sold from 178c to 300c while grown heifers made 196c to 274c/kg.  Store cows sold from 50c to 200c while medium cows made 190c to 212c and prime cows returned 220c to 252c lifting 5c/kg.
Shipping bulls gained 20c selling from 170c to 342c and the limited supply of Slaughter bulls ranged from 120c to 246c/kg.
Terry Birkin MLA.
